sdfsdf

Data Exploration¶

This dataset is a slightly modified version of the imagenette 320 px dataset from fastai. This contains 10 classes: cassetePlayer, ChainShaw, Church, EnglishSpringer, FrenchHorn, GarbageTruck, GasPump, GolfBall, parachute, tench.

pre-work¶

this step, we retrieve data from the path, then specify the size and batch, to settle down three datasets: train,validation, test.

In [217]:
train_dataset_path = '/kaggle/input/imagenettetvt320/train'
validation_dataset_path = '/kaggle/input/imagenettetvt320/val'
test_dataset_path ='/kaggle/input/imagenettetvt320/test'

Initial CNN¶

we build a rough CNN first.

model building¶

simply conv, pool, flatten, fully conntect layers. Here we don't input data or compile, we just want to see the architecture.

In [236]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(224, 224, 3))
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=30,kernel_size=3,strides=(3,3),activation="relu")(inputs)                 
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=60,kernel_size=3,strides=(3,3),activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(80, activation="relu")(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(50, activation="relu")(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(10, activation="softmax")(x)
m1 = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
m1.summary()

manual sumary of model¶

input:224,224,3

conv:(w-k+2p)/s+1=(224-3+2*0)/3+1=74,74,30

pool:(74-2)/2+1=37,37,30

conv: (37-3+2x0)/3+1=12,12,60

pool: (12-2)/2+1=6,6,60

flatten: 6x6x60=2160

fully connected layer: 1

verify if it is overfitting¶
In [239]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
accuracy = history.history["accuracy"]
val_accuracy = history.history["val_accuracy"]
loss = history.history["loss"]
val_loss = history.history["val_loss"]
epochs = range(1, len(accuracy) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, accuracy, "bo", label="Training accuracy")
plt.plot(epochs, val_accuracy, "b", label="Validation accuracy")
plt.title("Training and validation accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.figure()
plt.plot(epochs, loss, "bo", label="Training loss")
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, "b", label="Validation loss")
plt.title("Training and validation loss")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
from above: on validation dataset, accuracy stops improving at a point, and loss keeps increasing. And whether for accuracy or loss, from the score they always behave worse than train data.¶

Augmentation¶

we "zoom in" the data, as augmentation can help improve generalization--exposing data to a wider range of variations, such as changing orientation, flipping, rescale, lighting...

augmentation¶
In [241]:
data_augmentation = keras.Sequential(
    [
        layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
        layers.RandomRotation(0.1),
        layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
        layers.RandomBrightness(factor=0.5),

    ]
)

feature extraction plus data augmentation¶

use a pre-trained model¶
vgg, resnet, inception, mobilenet, can all be used as pre-trained CNN models. I randomly select one to see how it performs. Maybe next time I can change to another one.¶
In [251]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.resnet50 import ResNet50
conv_base =  ResNet50(
    weights="imagenet",
    include_top=False)

conv_base.trainable = False

combine with data augmentation¶
In [254]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.resnet50 import preprocess_input

data_augmentation = keras.Sequential(
    [
        layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
        layers.RandomRotation(0.1),
        layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
        layers.RandomBrightness(factor=0.5),

    ]
)


inputs = keras.Input(shape=(224,224, 3))
x = data_augmentation(inputs)
x = keras.applications.resnet50.preprocess_input(x)
x = conv_base(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dense(400)(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(10, activation="softmax")(x)
m3 = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)
m3.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy",
              optimizer="rmsprop",
              metrics=["accuracy"])

In [262]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
accuracy = history3.history["accuracy"]
val_accuracy = history3.history["val_accuracy"]
loss = history3.history["loss"]
val_loss = history3.history["val_loss"]
epochs = range(1, len(accuracy) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, accuracy, "bo", label="Training accuracy")
plt.plot(epochs, val_accuracy, "b", label="Validation accuracy")
plt.title("Training and validation accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.figure()
plt.plot(epochs, loss, "bo", label="Training loss")
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, "b", label="Validation loss")
plt.title("Training and validation loss")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
for the validatin data: for accuracy, it doesn't change much, but very high at always; for loss, it doesn't change much neither, and is very low at always. Just by talking about scores, in either scenarios they behave no worse than train.¶

fine tune this model¶

Here we randomly choose to inversely freeze all layers until the fourth one¶
In [261]:
conv_base.trainable = True
for layer in conv_base.layers[:-4]:
    layer.trainable = False
